******
[2]
Date: Fri 17 Oct 2014
Source: The Enterprise [edited]
http://www.enterprisenews.com/article/20141017/NEWS/141016883/12153/NEWS


The Massachusetts Department of Public Health on [Fri 17 Oct 2014] announced the 2nd case of eastern equine encephalitis [EEE] in a mammal this year [2014]. The infection was found in a 5 year old horse from Westminster, a town located in Worcester County. The horse was euthanized because of the severity of its illness. This finding raises the EEE risk level to critical in Westminster and to high in neighboring towns.

A deer with the disease (EEE) was found in Freetown [Bristol County] in August [2014]. The risk level is considered high in Freetown and moderate in neighboring communities.

Mosquito activity generally slows when the temperature is below 60 deg F [15.5 deg F], but the risk of the diseases remains until the 1st frost.

There have been no human cases EEE this year [2014]. There have been 4 human cases of West Nile virus - another mosquitoborne infection. Last year, there was one human case of EEE in Massachusetts.

--
